Data Visualization Assignment 2¶

Ahmed Rafiullah¶

01-249182-003

MSDS-1

Objective¶

Calculate similarity measure by different distance measures like Manhattan, Euclidean, Jaccard, Cosine etc on the samples of 3 different datasets and visulize the similarities.

Note : For visualization clustering was needed since since a large heat matrix would not be interpretable without it.

Import Libraries¶

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from scipy.spatial import distance
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import dendrogram, linkage
plt.rcParams['figure.facecolor'] = '1.0'

Description of data sets¶

Customer Segmentation¶

Obtained from https://www.kaggle.com/vjchoudhary7/customer-segmentation-tutorial-in-python Note: https://www.kaggle.com/kushal1996/customer-segmentation-k-means-analysis in this kernel you can see that kmeans and our results are quite similar. In the link number of clusters was given but not in our case.

MPG¶

This dataset contains a subset of the fuel economy data that the EPA makes available on http://fueleconomy.gov. It contains only models which had a new release every year between 1999 and 2008 - this was used as a proxy for the popularity of the car.

In [10]:
# Use euclidean pairwise distance
dense_matrix = distance.pdist(normalized_data, 'euclidean')

Plot similarities¶

In [11]:
# perform hierarchical clustering 
Z = linkage(dense_matrix, 'average')
square_matrix = distance.squareform(dense_matrix)
# set the heatmap color
colormapping  = "Blues_r"
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,figsize=(45, 55))
# plot the dendogram representation of the clusters
dn = dendrogram(Z, show_leaf_counts = True, leaf_font_size = 10, ax = ax[0])
ax[0].set_title(label = "Dendogram of the agglomerative hierarchical clustering", fontsize = 20)
# plot the matrix as it is
sns.heatmap( square_matrix, ax = ax[1], cmap=colormapping).set_title("Heat Matrix without Clustering", fontsize = 20)
# plot the matrix and clusters provide precomputed clustered matrix
sns.clustermap(square_matrix,figsize=(35, 25) ,row_linkage = Z, col_linkage = Z, cmap= colormapping )
fig.suptitle("Plot showing the clusters in customer segmentation datasets. Similarity calculated using Euclidean distance", fontsize = 20)
# convert square matrix to dataframe
pd.DataFrame(square_matrix).head(5)

# perform hierarchical clustering 
Z = linkage(dense_matrix, 'average')
square_matrix = distance.squareform(dense_matrix)
# set the heatmap color
colormapping  = "Blues_r"
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,figsize=(45, 55))
# plot the dendogram representation of the clusters
dn = dendrogram(Z, show_leaf_counts = True, leaf_font_size = 10, ax = ax[0])
ax[0].set_title(label = "Dendogram of the agglomerative hierarchical clustering", fontsize = 20)
# plot the matrix as it is
sns.heatmap( square_matrix, ax = ax[1], cmap=colormapping).set_title("Heat Matrix without Clustering", fontsize = 20)
# plot the matrix and clusters provide precomputed clustered matrix
sns.clustermap(square_matrix,figsize=(35, 25) ,row_linkage = Z, col_linkage = Z, cmap= colormapping )
fig.suptitle("Plot showing the clusters in MPG dataset. Similarity calculated using Euclidean distance", fontsize = 20)
